comments.body: I had a feeling this was mojave milkweed!
Also, thanks for the ID! I'll see if I can dig up any others of these to put on here & see if I can get them figured out.
I didn't collect any, alas. This was actually a nice little population, usually with oenotheroides / nyctaginifolia it seems like I just see a lone individual out in the middle of nowhere.

Chunky corona is the main difference.  Hybrids are expected in that area, but I've never seen a specimen that looks intermediate between these species.  Would be great to have additional samples from this area for molecular work.  Got any?
Perhaps it is a hybrid?  Both species occur in that area

I've never been able to sort out the difference between Asclepias oenotheroides and Asclepias nyctaginifolia. Everything seems to key out to oenotheroides in the keys I have on hand, but I've never had some nice definitely IDed plants to compare the two. Maybe @milkweedguy can help.
Hoods are fatter and corolla is not as reflexed

results.description: Asclepias oenotheroides, northwestern foothills of the Black Range between Beaver Creek and Kemp Mesa, southeast of Beaver Points, 33.369 -108.116, Catron County, New Mexico, 12 Aug 2016.
